><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>7458</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>British Academy Small Research Grant 2</gtr:description><gtr:end>2012-09-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>The British Academy</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>SG110838</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>C081A424-5071-4D57-AEC7-C7B36CBC6426</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5ec4cfea5ec4cff4</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2011-10-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>1. Keith Hyams has published a summary of some of the key findings of the research project in widely-read newsletters of think tanks the Fabian Society and Policy Network. 'The Fair Society', Fabian Society Essays, August 2012


'Luck Egalitarianism: Fairness and Responsibility in an Unequal Society', Policy Network Opinions, August 2012

2. Details the significant impacts felt both for academic research on justice The research has already had a significant impact on academic debates about justice through its published findings, and through dissemination at conferences and at the high-profile project workshops, attended by leading contributors to the field. Further impacts are expected as more of the projects findings are published. Key impacts on academic debates are as follows:
i. The overwhelmingly popular view that it is possible to reconcile freedom and equality in an overall theory of justice has been undermined, opening up deep and important questions about how it is that we can maintain an intuitive commitment to both these values.
ii. Longstanding views about the nature of, and underlying grounds for, popular left-libertarian and luck-egalitarian theories of justice have been questioned, with the result that debate about these issues has been reopened.
iii. A clearer understanding of the nature of consent, and the scope of its power to legitimize, has informed thinking in applied areas such as rape law.

3. In June 2012 the project is organising a policy-focused conference that has already become a very high profile event attracting widespread interest. It will make a major contribution to shaping both public and political debate and informing policymaking about how to design policies that are fair, sensitive to issues of responsibility, and effective in overcoming inequality. The conference aims to foster ongoing collaborations that will maximize the social impact of the research. The project is hosting in June 2012 a major public conference, to which leading parliamentarians, policymakers, thinktanks and academic have been invited, to discuss the impacts of its research for public policy. The PI is working closely with the public policy manager and the press office at the AHRC to maximise the impact of the conference on shaping public debate and policy. Details of the conference are as follows:
In the wake of the financial crisis there has been a renewed interested in issues of fairness and responsibility. But what do these notions really mean? And how should they be applied to the social issues of our time? At same time there is concern at the increase in social and economic inequality, both nationally and globally. Which types of inequality ought be of primary concern, and what can be done about them? How does the recent emphasis on fairness and responsibility fit with the aim of reducing inequality? Can appeals to such notions help to reduce inequality, or do they detract from such efforts? What role ought such notions play in international efforts to reduce poverty and encourage development?
Confirmed participants include:
