4. Talk based on project research on what equality of opportunity requires in terms of policies for people with disabilities, hosted by March of Dimes Canada, Canada's leading disability advocacy organisation Shaped public debate by describing new perspectives on equality of opportunity for people with disabilities</gtr:description><gtr:id>6720A9F3-A561-4CBC-A1B9-F27FD157FC13</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural,Societal,Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>m-7642506610.269198de283658</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The project sought to examine the nature of, and grounds for, a commitment to equality and freedom in popular 'left-libertarian' theories of justice. It further sought to describe how such commitments ought be implemented in matters of public policy. The key findings of the project are as follows:



1. Dominant theories of justice including left-libertarianism and so-called 'luck egalitarianism' claim that it is possible to incorporate both a commitment to equality and a commitment to freedom within an overall theory of justice. The project demonstrates that those who think such a reconciliation possible misunderstand the moral nature of freedom, or equality, or both. This finding has led to important and potentially revisionary new insights about how political philosophers should use 'intuitions' to support principled claims, to be pursued further by Dr. Hyams in a Leverhulme-funded fellowship commencing October 2012.



2. A commitment to freedom is best understood as a commitment to the legitimising power of consent and the protective power of rights. Current theories of the scope of consent's power to legitimise are seriously inadequate: a new theory was described.



3. Left-libertarians claim that agents are entitled to an equal endowment of resources at the start of their lives. This claim can be grounded in a conception of equality of opportunity, a constituent of justice. The conception of equality of opportunity requires constraints on permissible inheritance. Nevertheless, justice is not exhausted by the provision of an initial endowment of resources or by constraints on inheritance: it also makes other demands, as detailed in the following key findings. 



4. The model of equality of opportunity required by justice requires changes to the model of equality of opportunity that dominates present policymaking. In particular, a just conception of equality of opportunity requires not only that people have an equal opportunity to pursue positions of advantage, but also that inequalities between available positions themselves be diminished.



5. Justice requires that people be provided with the opportunity to insure against any significant risks that they face later on in their lives. It is unfair that agents suffer unequally at the hands of risks that they would prefer to avoid and are unable to insure against. The project provides a novel explanation of this unfairness.



6. In order to better meet the challenges posed by justice, current approaches to taxation and public services would have to be reformed in significant ways. Various options for reform, which would better achieve the requirements of justice whilst maintaining economic growth, were examined. The project also explored how the requirements of justice could be met at the international level through reforms to international aid and development practices.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>In the wake of the financial crisis, questions about fairness, inequality and responsibility have taken centre stage in government. The findings of the research project speak directly to these political debates, with particular significance for government policy in the areas of social and economic equality, public services and tax, and poverty prevention. These themes will be explored in depth at a conference in June 2012, which has already engaged considerable high-profile interest. The conference brings the PI, Co-I and project PhD student together with leading parliamentarians, policymakers and senior representatives of influential political think-tanks, including Rachel Reeves MP, Will Hutton, The Equality Trust, The Fabian Society, Institute for Public Policy Research, Oxfam, Overseas Development Institute, Social Research Unit, and the Policy Network.



Considerations of both fairness and consent are at the heart of a number of further policy issues. Through talks to academic and non-academic audiences, we have already begun to explore their implications for accessibility policies for people with disabilities, for policies to tackle climate change, for medical ethics, and for rape law.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>EB66CEE4-BF18-48C1-AAF9-D9D9ED78260A</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-2654408833.621450477924bc4</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Financial Services, and Management Consultancy,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>3AD7F654-DA8E-45A5-ABD8-5810465A8B11</gtr:id><gtr:title>Need There be a Defence of Equality? Winner of the 2010 Postgraduate Essay Prize</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Res Publica</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/33670dc6ffe3bbb8fe0780b838f4fccb"><gtr:id>33670dc6ffe3bbb8fe0780b838f4fccb</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Nathan C</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfdefde5d7553f</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>022A8C3D-8763-43CA-BD92-84CF9E601DEF</gtr:id><gtr:title>Hypothetical Choice, Egalitarianism and the Separateness of Persons</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Utilitas</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/97f6d9df0818f2d0e69a9f865df92eba"><gtr:id>97f6d9df0818f2d0e69a9f865df92eba</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>HYAMS K</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>56d0ca26acccc0.46905981</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>B5A291B8-B2FB-